69 "      In number theory a number k (positive integer) is said to be
 a " }{TEXT 257 14 "proper divisor" }{TEXT -1 94 " of a number n (posi
tive integer) if \n                                       (i)  k divid
es n " }{TEXT 258 3 "and" }{TEXT -1 91 "  (ii) if k < n.\n      In num
ber theory a number n (positive integer) said to be:\n         " }
{TEXT 256 23 "               abundant" }{TEXT -1 54 " if the sum of th
e proper divisors of n is more than n" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 24 "
                        " }{TEXT 259 7 "perfect" }{TEXT -1 78 " if the
 sum of the proper divisors of n is equal to n\n                      \+
  " }{TEXT 260 9 "deficient" }{TEXT -1 248 " if the sum of the proper \+
divisors of n is less than n\n       c1.  Use Maple to find 2 numbers \+
which are abundant.  (Hint:  it may help to know the prime factorizati
on (guaranteed by the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra) of your abundant
 candidates.)" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 12 "ifactor(24)
